him is justice
for Hogan. It seems that what is
motivating

25:08.607 --> 25:12.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him is essentially crushing
Gawker through
the court system.

25:12.578 --> 25:15.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are a lot of people, a
lot of people
in the press in particular, who
see that and

25:15.981 --> 25:22.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get very, very scared, because
the point isn't
even necessarily to win the
suit. He can continue

25:22.321 --> 25:27.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to litigate against Gawker and
rack up huge
legal fees and destroy them even
if he never

25:27.259 --> 25:29.094 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wins a suit.

25:29.128 --> 25:33.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, what does
the tech community
in Silicon Valley, how do they
feel about

25:33.432 --> 25:36.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this? On the one hand, there's
the journalism
question. On the other hand,
there is that

25:36.468 --> 25:39.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Peter Thiel is a smart guy and a
visionary
in this community.

25:39.738 --> 25:44.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JASON TANZ: Yes, there's been a
lot of defense
of Thiel within the tech
community.

25:44.309 --> 25:47.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gawker is an easy media property
to hate.
And Valleywag in particular, for
those in

25:47.780 --> 25:53.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the tech industry, is a very
easy media property
to hate. They were glib, they
were cruel,

25:53.085 --> 25:57.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they were callous, and they had,
some would
say, pretty bad editorial
judgment a lot of

25:57.189 --> 25:58.957 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the time,

25:58.991 --> 26:02.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like lot a First Amendment
cases, whether
that is Larry Flynt or Gawker,
it's very hard

26:02.428 --> 26:08.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to defend the specifics of this
particular
case. So, a lot of people within
Silicon Valley

26:08.367 --> 26:14.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are saying, look, this isn't any
different
from the ACLU or Greenpeace
funding suits

26:14.072 --> 26:18.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they think are going to end
up having
a greater social good.

26:18.210 --> 26:22.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In this case, the greater social
good is punishing
and deterring people from
publishing the kind

26:22.648 --> 26:28.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of stuff that Gawker does. Now,
the concern,
of course, is who is to
determine what should

26:28.287 --> 26:31.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be punished? And even if we all
agree -- and
I'm not saying that we do -- but
even if we

26:31.924 --> 26:35.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
