published shouldn't
have been published, by that
same logic, you

26:35.928 --> 26:40.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
could say, I don't like the way
they're talking
about Theranos, and that's
really been unfair

26:40.365 --> 26:44.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Theranos, and I think that
that has been
unfair and untoward and is
click-bait, and,

26:44.970 --> 26:48.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
therefore, I'm going to punish
The Wall Street
Journal for publishing that.

26:48.440 --> 26:51.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's one of those slippery slope
arguments
that you get into with these
First Amendment

26:51.577 --> 26:52.945 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
disputes.

26:52.978 --> 26:55.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Jason Tanz from
"Wired," thanks so much.

26:55.347 --> 27:04.890 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JASON TANZ: Yes, thanks for
having me.

27:04.923 --> 27:11.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Much of the focus on
Latinos throughout
this election cycle has centered
on the divisive

27:11.597 --> 27:15.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and often heated questions about
immigration
and its effects.

27:15.400 --> 27:21.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But now a bipartisan non-profit
group is trying
to change that. The Latino Donor
Collective

27:21.740 --> 27:26.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
(sic), as it's known, wants to
emphasize the
growing economic power of
Latinos and the

27:26.078 --> 27:28.180 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
potential force they can become.

27:28.213 --> 27:35.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spoke with its co-founders,
Democrat Henry
Cisneros and Republican
businessman Sol Trujillo.

27:35.053 --> 27:38.423 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Cisneros was housing secretary
in the Clinton
administration.

27:38.457 --> 27:40.893 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Gentlemen, thanks for being with
us.

27:40.926 --> 27:42.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mr. Cisneros, I would like to
start with you.

27:42.728 --> 27:46.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The two of you wrote an essay
for The Wall
Street Journal, and you said
that you have

27:46.365 --> 27:51.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been watching this presidential
campaign unfold
at first with disappointment,
then with concern

27:51.470 --> 27:54.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and now with real alarm. What is
alarming
you?

27:54.473 --> 27:58.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HENRY CISNEROS, Co-Founder,
Latino Donor Collaborative:
Well, what alarms me is that the
rhetoric

27:58.477 --> 28:06.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about Latinos seems to be giving
people permission
to denigrate this population, to
diminish

28:06.818 --> 28:10.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
its place in American life. And
that's just
wrong.

28:10.722 --> 28:16.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a population of 55
million people,
growing to 100 million people.
It is essential

28:16.862 --> 28:23.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the American future. It is
already making
a major contribution in many
areas of American

28:23.168 --> 28:33.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
life, from religion to politics
to entrepreneurship
and to corporate business and as
consumers.

28:33.512 --> 28:39.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of the most important
areas is in
its contribution to the American
economy,

28:39.484 --> 28:46.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what Sol has come to call the
mainstream economy,
the mainstream American economy,
the next

28:46.191 --> 28:55.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American economy. And it's just
wrong to categorize
a people somehow as -- using
phrases related

28:55.067 --> 29:01.640 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to rapists and murderers and
freeloaders,
et cetera, to characterize an
entire population.

29:01.673 --> 29:07.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And someone needs to stand up
and say, let's
talk about the truth of this
population. And

29:07.245 --> 29:08.947 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it's role in American life.

29:08.981 --> 29:11.917 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Trujillo, why are
the politicians
missing this? What aren't they
getting?

29:11.950 --> 29:15.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOL TRUJILLO, Co-Founder, Latino
Donor Collaborative:
No one talking how we drive
growth, how we're

29:15.921 --> 29:21.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
creating jobs, what's creating
jobs, what
is our upside in terms of the
economy.

29:21.259 --> 29:27.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And is where today we have a new
mainstream
economy driven predominantly by
Latinos in

29:27.332 --> 29:31.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
growth. Let me give you some
quick statistics.
There's about a
trillion-and-a-half dollars

29:31.703 --> 29:37.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of spend by Latinos in this
country today,
growing at $80 billion to $90
billion per

29:37.442 --> 29:39.211 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
year.

29:39.244 --> 29:44.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On top that, let's talk about
job creation
and what are drivers of domestic
GDP growth.

29:44.883 --> 29:51.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Think about housing. Think about
home purchases.
Over the last decade, 51 percent
of all new

29:51.556 --> 29:57.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
home mortgages taken out in the
United States
of America have been taken out
by Latino families.

29:57.996 --> 30:03.635 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
When you look at
entrepreneurship, in the
last half-decade, 86 percent of
all new business

30:03.669 --> 30:09.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
formations in the United States,
based upon
a recent Hoover study
commissioned through

30:09.508 --> 30:17.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the Stanford Latino
Entrepreneurship Initiative,
shows that Latinos were creating
86 percent

30:17.449 --> 30:19.584 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of all new business formations.

30:19.618 --> 30:26.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Without Latinos in the mix, we
as a nation
would have had net negative
business formations.

30:26.558 --> 30:32.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I can go on with more data,
John. But,
as an American, as somebody that
cares about

30:32.664 --> 30:37.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our economy, which all of us at
the Latino
Donor Collaborative do, we want
to make sure

30:37.669 --> 30:45.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that this story is understood,
rather than
mischaracterizations, incorrect
facts, which

30:45.544 --> 30:51.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will mislead policy decisions
that could be
very damaging to our economy.

30:51.316 --> 30:56.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Mr. Cisneros, you
talk about the
-- sort of the economic drivers
in the Latino

30:56.455 --> 31:01.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
community. But at the same time,
there are
economic challenges to the
Latino community.

31:01.193 --> 31:07.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The BLS, Bureau of Labor
Statistics, says
that one in five Latinos is
working in a minimum

31:07.065 --> 31:12.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
wage job, that unemployment
among Latinos
is higher than the national
average. Are there

31:12.504 --> 31:16.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
still challenges among the --
for Latinos
in the economy?

31:16.108 --> 31:22.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HENRY CISNEROS: Oh, absolutely.
There are
huge challenges, many Latinos
working in underemployed

31:22.247 --> 31:25.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
situations, undercompensated
situations.

31:25.250 --> 31:29.054 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And one of the biggest
challenges confronting
the Latino community is the need
to close

31:29.087 --> 31:35.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the gap in educational levels.
And we are.
We're making progress in terms
of lowering

31:35.393 --> 31:39.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the dropout rate, improving the
high school
graduation rate, improving the
acception to

31:39.998 --> 31:41.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
college.

31:41.767 --> 31:45.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But one of the most dangerous
things about
the kind of rhetoric we're
seeing today is

31:45.137 --> 31:51.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that if it results in the
country failing
to recognize that it must invest
in Latinos,

31:51.409 --> 31:56.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that Latinos are ambitious
and want to
avail themselves of education
and providing

31:56.581 --> 32:02.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the means to do that, then
there's a huge
opportunity cost for the United
States.

32:02.554 --> 32:08.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a population that is
large. In fact,
it's going to be 100 million
people by about

32:08.093 --> 32:12.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
2040, 25 percent of the American
population.
It's already the largest
minority and the

32:12.964 --> 32:19.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fastest growing minority. The
swing can be
immense. Either it can be a
large population

32:19.437 --> 32:24.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is a drag on American
society because
it is not receiving the proper
education and

32:24.509 --> 32:30.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
proper investment, or it can be
truly one
of the absolute drivers, one of
the engines

32:30.482 --> 32:33.552 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of opportunity for the American
future, without
a doubt.

32:33.585 --> 32:39.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: How can you get the
political power
to match the demographic power
and the economic

32:39.958 --> 32:46.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
power? In 20 -- the last
presidential election,
only 47 percent of Latinos
registered to vote

32:46.832 --> 32:47.532 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
voted.

32:47.566 --> 32:49.501 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How can you improve that
turnout?

32:49.534 --> 32:56.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOL TRUJILLO: Well, John, let's
look at results
first before we get into the
what I call misleading

32:56.274 --> 32:58.043 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
statistical analysis.

32:58.076 --> 33:04.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If you look at the last
election, one of the
big conclusions of the
Republican Party was

33:04.416 --> 33:09.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the reason why they lost
was because
of the fact that they didn't get
the Latino

33:09.921 --> 33:16.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
vote. If you look at the prior
election, same
conclusion, and the one before
that, until

33:16.161 --> 33:22.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you look back at George W. Bush,
and you look
at Ronald Reagan, who both were
able to get

33:22.167 --> 33:24.769 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over 40 percent of the Latino
vote.

33:24.803 --> 33:31.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, guess what? The base of
the Latino vote,
the percentage of total voters
as Latinos

33:31.843 --> 33:38.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has only gotten bigger. So, I
call it basic
elementary math. Then you have
to understand

33:38.383 --> 33:46.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the basic math. We can talk
about 47 percent
voter rates or we can talk about
42 and talk

33:46.391 --> 33:49.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about those numbers, but the
base is just
getting bigger.

33:49.961 --> 33:57.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's the reality. There's
almost a million
young Latinos turning 18 every
year; 93 percent

33:57.135 --> 34:03.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of them are native-born. And
it's dramatically
changing what we would call the
base, the

34:03.041 --> 34:08.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
voter base, those who are going
to be active
in politics, and while at the
same time, other

34:08.413 --> 34:13.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
groups are actually in decline
as a percentage
of total. It's just math.

34:13.251 --> 34:17.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Sol Trujillo, Henry
Cisneros, trying
to change the discussion about
Latinos in

34:17.689 --> 34:19.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
America, thanks for joining us.

34:19.090 --> 34:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HENRY CISNEROS: Thank you for
the opportunity.

34:20.592 --> 34:22.360 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SOL TRUJILLO: Thank you, John.

34:22.394 --> 34:26.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The group that Mr.
Cisneros and
Mr. Trujillo have started is the
Latino Donor

34:26.631 --> 34:30.635 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Collaborative.

